that has raised questions. Some
leaders in

12:36.990 --> 12:40.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
higher education and nonprofits
have also
expressed a fear about what this
could do

12:40.960 --> 12:42.729 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to their work force as well.

12:42.762 --> 12:49.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
THOMAS PEREZ: Well, we have done
a lot of
discussion with higher ed. And
what they learned

12:49.302 --> 12:53.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when we would discuss this issue
with them
is, they have remarkable amounts
of flexibility

12:53.773 --> 12:56.075 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that they were unaware of.

12:56.109 --> 13:00.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We had someone from higher ed
say, oh, my
God, my teachers work 70 hours a
week, and

13:00.179 --> 13:04.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
now have I to pay them overtime.
Well, actually,
that's not true, because the
Fair Labor Standards

13:04.617 --> 13:10.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Act exempts teachers, it exempts
research
assistants, it exempts wide
categories of

13:10.790 --> 13:12.558 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
employees.

13:12.592 --> 13:15.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I heard from a public university
about all
the challenges of compliance,
but they were

13:15.928 --> 13:23.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
unaware of the fact that public
universities
can give comp time, in lieu of
overtime pay,

13:23.302 --> 13:29.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for these workers. And when they
heard that,
you should have seen them. The
lightbulb be

13:29.442 --> 13:31.144 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
went off.

13:31.177 --> 13:36.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think there is a pretty
good road
map for compliance for folks in
higher ed.

13:36.416 --> 13:43.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I would note this, William,
which is that,
you know, over 50 percent of the
4.2 million

13:43.723 --> 13:48.361 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
workers who are going to
directly benefit
from this rule have a college
degree. And

13:48.394 --> 13:50.163 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
over 80 percent have some
college.

13:50.196 --> 13:56.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I always thought the mission of
higher ed
was to help prepare workers so
that they can

13:57.003 --> 14:01.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be productive citizens and punch
their ticket
to the middle class. So, you
know, it's a

14:01.674 --> 14:07.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
little inconsistent to have that
mission and
then say, well, hey, wait a
minute, we shouldn't

14:07.447 --> 14:14.253 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
be raising wages of our
graduates, especially
when I see the salaries of,
like, the football

14:14.287 --> 14:18.224 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
coach at a couple of the
universities that
came to talk to us.

14:18.257 --> 14:22.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you pay them five, six,
seven million
dollars a year, you ought to be
able to figure

14:22.729 --> 14:29.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out a way to make sure that the
person who
manages the cafeteria in one of
your halls

14:29.135 --> 14:31.404 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
can get a middle-class salary.

14:31.437 --> 14:35.208 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Labor Secretary
Thomas Perez, thanks very much
for joining

14:35.241 --> 14:36.943 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
us.

14:36.976 --> 14:43.950 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
THOMAS PEREZ: Thank you.

14:43.983 --> 14:49.222 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to Libya.

14:49.255 --> 14:53.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chaos has gripped the North
African nation
since the fall of Moammar
Gadhafi, with at

14:53.760 --> 14:59.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
least two governments and
multiple factions
simultaneously vying for power.
Now there's

14:59.665 --> 15:06.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
word of wholesale atrocities by
Islamic State
forces in the coastal city of
Sirte.

15:06.906 --> 15:13.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Fighter jets flying for Libya's
U.N.-backed
government are bombing around
Sirte, and allied

15:13.613 --> 15:19.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ground forces are pushing back
as well to
stop Islamic State militants
from expanding

15:19.485 --> 15:26.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
beyond their stronghold there;
120 miles of
the Central Libyan coastline in
and around

15:26.359 --> 15:32.031 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Sirte has been under the
militant group's
control since early 2015.

15:32.064 --> 15:38.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nearly two-thirds of Sirte's
80,000 people
have fled, and been forced to
rely on humanitarian

15:38.704 --> 15:40.506 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
aid.

15:40.540 --> 15:45.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): The
nationalities
of ISIS fighters are all
foreign, Tunisians,

15:45.645 --> 15:50.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Egyptians, Sudanese. They came
in and created
a state of fear and terror for
the people

15:50.783 --> 15:55.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and families, so we fled. And
they're all
foreigners. None of them are
Libyans. We fled

15:55.922 --> 15:57.623 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with nothing.

15:57.657 --> 16:02.028 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now come
disturbing details
of what's happening inside Sirte
in a Human

16:02.061 --> 16:08.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Rights Watch report based on
interviews with
those who left. It tells of
dozens of beheadings

16:08.334 --> 16:14.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
by sword, floggings and
crucifixions, fathers
forced to marry off their
daughters to ISIS

16:14.874 --> 16:21.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fighters, and all females over
the age of
10 forced to wear the
conservative black cloak,

16:21.147 --> 16:23.115 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the abaya.

16:23.149 --> 16:28.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On Monday in Vienna, Secretary
of State John
Kerry announced an agreement to
arm the internationally

16:28.888 --> 16:33.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
recognized government in the
fight against
ISIS, also called Da'esh:

16:33.626 --> 16:38.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN KERRY, U.S. Secretary of
State: The international
community will support the
Presidency Council

16:38.231 --> 16:44.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as it seeks exemption from the
U.N. arms embargo
to acquire those weapons and
bullets need

16:44.904 --> 16:48.140 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to fight Da'esh and other
terrorist groups.

16:48.174 --> 16:53.813 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But it won't be
easy. The U.S.
commander in Africa, General
David Rodriguez,

16:53.846 --> 16:59.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
said yesterday it's hard to tell
which of
many armed groups have aligned
with the U.N.-supported

16:59.719 --> 17:03.189 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
regime and which have not.

17:03.222 --> 17:07.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we take a closer look at
those groups
and what the United States is
doing in Libya.

17:07.860 --> 17:12.298 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm joined now by Frederic
Wehrey of the Middle
East Program at the Carnegie
Endowment for

17:12.331 --> 17:17.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
International Peace. He was a
military attache
to the U.S. Embassy in Tripoli
during the

17:18.004 --> 17:22.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
George W. Bush administration,
and he visits
the country regularly.

17:22.341 --> 17:24.277 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Fred Wehrey, welcome back to the
program.

17:24.310 --> 17:26.078 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FREDERIC WEHREY, Carnegie
Endowment for International
Peace: Great to be here.

17:26.112 --> 17:29.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Remind us again
how Libya got
to this state, two warring
governments the

17:29.148 --> 17:31.517 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
same time, multiple fighting
groups.

17:31.550 --> 17:35.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FREDERIC WEHREY: Well, ever
since the fall
of Gadhafi, there has been a
governance vacuum.

17:35.087 --> 17:41.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, the country has split
into civil war
since 2014, two governments, two
sets of militias.

17:41.193 --> 17:46.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is this new U.N. unity
government in
Tripoli that is still very weak,
but the eastern

17:46.799 --> 17:50.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
faction doesn't recognize it. So
you have
got this vacuum. And that is a
ripe condition

17:50.603 --> 17:54.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for the Islamic State to insert
itself, as
they have in the town of Sirte.

17:54.373 --> 17:58.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, how strong is
ISIS, the
Islamic State, in Libya right
now?

17:58.711 --> 18:05.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FREDERIC WEHREY: The estimates
are about 3,000
to 6,000 fighters, bolstered by
foreign volunteers

18:05.051 --> 18:10.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from abroad. And they control
about 120 miles,
strip of coastline in the
center.

18:10.423 --> 18:16.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And how big a
threat does that
represent, given everything else
going on

18:16.195 --> 18:17.997 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Libya?

18:18.030 --> 18:22.034 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
FREDERIC WEHREY: It's
destabilizing to the
country's growth. It's also a
threat to Europe

18:22.068 --> 18:26.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and especially neighboring
states. We have
seen the Islamic State in Libya
plot attacks

18:26.138 --> 18:27.807 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
against neighboring Tunisia.

18:27.840 --> 18:31.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And so, well,
let's back off
a little bit here and go back to
the role

18:32.011 --> 18:36.282 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the United States. You just
mentioned NATO.

18:36.315 --> 18:41.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What does this mean? The U.S.
was out of Libya.
Then it was in, out. Where is
the U.S. right

18:41.554 --> 18:43.289 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
now in Libya?

18:43.322 --> 18:47.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FREDERIC WEHREY: Well, the U.S.
is really
behind this new unity government
in Tripoli.

18:47.860 --> 18:51.597 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they are obviously focused
on the Islamic
State threat.

18:51.630 --> 18:55.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think, more broadly, the
U.S. wants
to ensure that this government
succeeds, that

18:55.801 --> 19:00.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we don't repeat the mistakes
that we made
after the fall of Gadhafi. But,
of course,

19:00.573 --> 19:06.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the first priority is protecting
this government
and then helping it fight the
Islamic State.

19:06.145 --> 19:09.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that's going to be
done through
some training, through
assistance, through

19:09.915 --> 19:12.051 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the lifting of the arms embargo,
as we heard.

19:12.084 --> 19:17.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But we also -- we
heard Secretary
Kerry say the U.S. is going to
be arming the

19:17.690 --> 19:23.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
right government. But we also
heard the general
say it's not clear which group
is which, on

19:23.496 --> 19:25.264 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
which side. How confusing is it?

19:25.297 --> 19:27.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FREDERIC WEHREY: Well, this is
-- it is very
confusing. This is the problem
we face in

19:27.700 --> 19:30.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all of these states where we're
fighting the
Islamic State. Who do you
partner with?

19:30.569 --> 19:34.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the case of Libya, there is
no unified
government, there is no unified
chain of command,

19:34.340 --> 19:38.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there is no unified army. So,
you have got
to pick among these militias.
And it is a

19:38.244 --> 19:41.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very dangerous game, because you
don't know
who you are dealing with. Those
militias may

19:41.747 --> 19:43.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
turn against you. They may turn
against one
another.

19:43.949 --> 19:48.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, a great risk is that, by
arming them,
we could actually fuel the civil
war. So,

19:48.154 --> 19:51.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think the general is very
right in proceeding
quite carefully.

19:51.557 --> 19:54.160 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you do
that? How does
the United States do that?

19:54.193 --> 19:58.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FREDERIC WEHREY: Well, there's
been reports
now of U.S. special operations
on the ground.

19:58.497 --> 20:03.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what they are trying to do
is assess these
militias, their capacity, their
will, who

20:03.069 --> 20:07.239 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are they aligned with, before
they begin training
and assisting them.

20:07.273 --> 20:11.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But you have got to vet them for
human rights
violations. You have got to
recruit the right

20:11.277 --> 20:14.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ones. But, more importantly, you
have got
to make sure that they are under
the control

20:14.447 --> 20:16.215 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of a democratic government.

20:16.248 --> 20:20.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What do you think
should be
done, Fred Wehrey? Is it your
sense that this

20:20.152 --> 20:23.189 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is a formula that is going to
move in the
right direction?

20:23.222 --> 20:27.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FREDERIC WEHREY: I think the
U.S. has learned
a great deal from the mistakes
they made.

20:27.493 --> 20:31.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think they're proceeding
quite cautiously.
I think the right approach is to
really support

20:31.697 --> 20:36.435 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the legitimacy of this new
government. This
has to be a Libyan-led fight.

20:36.469 --> 20:41.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the things that really
amazed me when
I was in Libya was the amount of
sort of societal

20:41.574 --> 20:45.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
resilience in Libya against the
Islamic State.
This was a foreign entity.
People don't want

20:45.911 --> 20:49.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it. The Libyans want to move
forward with
their government, with their
economy. And

20:49.915 --> 20:52.151 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
so the U.S. has to harness that
momentum.

20:52.184 --> 20:56.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, that's what
I was trying
to get at, as you know, because
we see ISIS

20:56.822 --> 21:01.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a factor in so many countries in
the region.
How do you tell the difference
between countries

21:01.327 --> 21:06.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where ISIS can overwhelm what is
on the ground
there, and where the forces
against it can

21:06.799 --> 21:08.667 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be stronger?

21:08.701 --> 21:11.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FREDERIC WEHREY: Yes, I mean, I
think we shouldn't
be overly alarmist about the
Islamic State

21:11.437 --> 21:15.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Libya. I mean, they are sort
of boxed in
the central region. They can
still do a lot

21:15.441 --> 21:20.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of damage. But it's not to the
extent that
they are in Iraq, say, or Syria.

21:20.546 --> 21:24.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Bottom line, Fred
Wehrey, what
is at stake here for the United
States?

21:24.783 --> 21:30.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FREDERIC WEHREY: Well, I think
what is at
stake is the success of the sort
of toppling

21:30.890 --> 21:36.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the Gadhafi government, I
mean, the security
of important allies in the
region, the security

21:36.529 --> 21:40.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of Europe. It's all wrapped up
together. So,
there is a lot at stake.

21:40.799 --> 21:43.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And Europe is
very much a part
of this. We haven't -- I haven't
asked you

21:43.802 --> 21:44.803 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about that, but that is very
much a...

21:44.837 --> 21:46.572 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

21:46.605 --> 21:48.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FREDERIC WEHREY: Right. They
are, absolutely.
I mean, they are directly
affected by it.

21:48.073 --> 21:48.908 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There are reports of...

21:48.941 --> 21:50.709 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Because of
refugees?

21:50.743 --> 21:53.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FREDERIC WEHREY: Well, because
of refugees,
then also the potential plotting
of terrorist

21:53.512 --> 21:56.282 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
attacks on Libyan soil against
Europe.

21:56.315 --> 22:00.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the French are reportedly on
the ground
with their special operations.
So are the

22:00.186 --> 22:05.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
British. The Italians have
really committed
to helping this government, to
help train

22:05.224 --> 22:07.026 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that new Libyan military.

22:07.059 --> 22:11.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, it is a
complicated story,
but it's an important one for us
to follow.

22:11.897 --> 22:14.967 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Fred Wehrey, thank you very
much.

22:15.000 --> 22:21.607 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FREDERIC WEHREY: Thanks for
having me. Thank
you.

22:21.640 --> 22:24.944 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Appreciate it.

