40:29.260 --> 40:35.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are still learning about the
aftermath, and
how some life is emerging from
the ashes.

40:35.300 --> 40:40.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Science correspondent Miles
O'Brien has the
story, part of our new weekly
series about

40:40.071 --> 40:43.141 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
exploring the Leading Edge of
science.

40:43.174 --> 40:49.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Thirty-six years
after its
spectacular, deadly eruption,
Mount St. Helens

40:49.480 --> 40:53.885 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
still rumbles and bears scars
from that earth-shattering
day.

40:53.918 --> 40:59.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But hike down the slopes, away
from that jagged
crater just a little, and you
will see Mother

40:59.290 --> 41:04.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nature hard at work. And there's
a good chance
you will bump into a team of
scientists led

41:04.896 --> 41:09.667 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
by John Bishop. He is an
evolutionary biologist
at Washington State
University-Vancouver.

41:09.701 --> 41:11.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN BISHOP, Evolutionary
Biologist, Washington
State University-Vancouver: The
goal of our

41:11.703 --> 41:17.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
research is to understand how
plant and animal
communities reform after a
catastrophic disturbance.

41:17.175 --> 41:22.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Bishop is one of
a select group
of researchers studying this
rebound from

41:22.780 --> 41:29.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
